Question:
Join all strings in a list into a single comma-separated string.
Input:
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("red", "blue", "green");

Solution:
Java 8 Streams join strings using collect(Collectors.joining(",")). For input ["red", "blue", "green"], it prints red,blue,green.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list via stream(). Collect with Collectors.joining(",") to concatenate using comma delimiter. Print the resulting single string.
​
#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class JoinStrings {
    public static void joinAndPrint(List<String> strings) {
        String result = strings.stream()
                               .collect(Collectors.joining(","));
        System.out.println(result);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> list = Arrays.asList("red", "blue", "green");
        joinAndPrint(list);
    }
}

Prints red,blue,green. joining(",") handles delimiter efficiently.
​
#Thought Process
joining(delimiter) collector reduces stream to String via StringBuilder internally. Comma-separated common; variants add prefix/suffix. Prefer over manual reduce for readability/performance.
​
#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty string "".​
Null list: NPE on stream(); null-check.
Null elements: "null" literal inserted; filter Objects::nonNull to skip.
Single element: Returns itself, no comma.
Large lists: Efficient O(n); parallelStream ok.
